---
import PublicLayout from '../../layouts/PublicLayout.astro';
---

<PublicLayout
  title="Flows — Mnema docs"
  description="What a flow is, how Claude calls one, and when to use a flow instead of a single doc."
  pathname="/docs/flows"
>
  <article class="max-w-[680px] mx-auto px-6 pt-[80px] pb-[96px]">
    <a
      href="/docs"
      class="transition-colors inline-block mb-8"
      style="font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-tertiary);"
      onmouseover="this.style.color='var(--text-primary)'"
      onmouseout="this.style.color='var(--text-tertiary)'"
    >
      ← All docs
    </a>

    <span
      class="block mb-3 font-mono uppercase"
      style="font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.08em; color: var(--text-tertiary);"
    >
      Flows
    </span>
    <h1
      style="font-size: 28px; line-height: 1.3; letter-spacing: -0.01em; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text-primary);"
    >
      Flows
    </h1>
    <p
      class="mt-3 mb-12"
      style="font-size: 15px; color: var(--text-secondary);"
    >
      Flows are how Mnema turns a workspace of docs into structured context for an AI agent.
      Here's what they are, how Claude calls them, and when to reach for one.
    </p>

    <ol class="space-y-8 list-none">
      {[
        {
          heading: 'What a flow is',
          body: (
            <span>
              A flow is a named sequence of content steps. Each step has an instruction and
              references one or more docs in your workspace. Flows are the unit of context
              that you deliver to Claude — not raw docs, not entire workspaces, but specific
              ordered sequences with your authorial intent baked in.
            </span>
          ),
        },
        {
          heading: 'How Claude calls a flow',
          body: (
            <span>
              Claude (or any MCP client) discovers your flows by calling{' '}
              <code style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; background: var(--surface-sunken); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); padding: 2px 6px; color: var(--text-primary);">list_flows</code>.
              It then walks the flow by calling{' '}
              <code style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; background: var(--surface-sunken); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); padding: 2px 6px; color: var(--text-primary);">get_flow_step(flow_id, step_number)</code>
              {' '}for each step in order. Each call returns one step's instruction plus the rendered content. The
              sequence is explicit — Claude doesn't decide order, you do.
            </span>
          ),
        },
        {
          heading: 'When to use a flow vs. a single doc',
          body: (
            <span>
              Single docs are good when Claude needs a fact or a specific piece of content.
              Flows are good when Claude needs to be walked through something — a codebase
              onboarding, a workflow, a structured analysis. If you'd brief a teammate over
              five minutes with "first read this, then this, then this" — that's a flow.
            </span>
          ),
        },
        {
          heading: 'The flow editor (coming next release)',
          body: (
            <span>
              The visual flow editor is in active development. Drag docs into a sequence,
              annotate each step with an instruction, save the flow. It's exposed to Claude
              automatically through MCP — no extra wiring needed.
            </span>
          ),
        },
      ].map((step, i) => (
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <div
            class="flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center font-mono font-medium"
            style="width: 28px; height: 28px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--surface-elevated); border: 1px solid var(--border-default); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-primary);"
          >
            {i + 1}
          </div>
          <div class="pt-0.5">
            <h2 style="font-size: 16px; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text-primary); line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 4px;">
              {step.heading}
            </h2>
            <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.65;">
              {step.body}
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ol>

    <div
      class="mt-16 p-6"
      style="background: var(--surface-overlay); border: 1px solid var(--border-default); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);"
    >
      <h3 style="font-size: 14px; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text-primary); margin-bottom: 8px;">
        Today vs. next release
      </h3>
      <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.65;">
        The MCP server already advertises{' '}
        <code style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; background: var(--surface-sunken); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); padding: 2px 6px; color: var(--text-primary);">list_flows</code>{' '}
        and{' '}
        <code style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px; background: var(--surface-sunken); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); padding: 2px 6px; color: var(--text-primary);">get_flow_step</code>{' '}
        as tools. They currently return an empty preview response — the flow editor fills
        them in. The contract is stable now so Claude conversations referencing flows will
        keep working when the editor ships.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</PublicLayout>
